  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law **prohibits money laundering** in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is illegal because it allows criminals to profit from their illegal activities while making the funds appear legitimate.\n\n### Key Legal Frameworks:\n1. **United States**: \n   - The **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** of 1970 requires financial institutions to report suspicious activities.\n   - The **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** explicitly criminalized money laundering.\n   - The **USA PATRIOT Act** of 2001 strengthened anti-money laundering (AML) measures.\n\n2. **European Union**:\n   - The **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** set out a comprehensive framework to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing across EU member states.\n\n3. **International**:\n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental body, sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Many countries adopt FATF recommendations into their national laws.\n\n### Penalties:\nMoney laundering is a serious criminal offense that can result in severe penalties, including:\n- Substantial fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Seizure of assets\n- Reputational damage for individuals and businesses involved\n\n### Enforcement:\nGovernments and regulatory bodies, such as financial intelligence units (FIUs), work closely with banks, businesses, and law enforcement agencies to detect, investigate, and prosecute money laundering activities. Compliance with anti-money laundering (AML) regulations is mandatory for financial institutions, requiring them to implement measures like customer due diligence (CDD) and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally prohibited by law, and efforts to combat it are a priority for governments and international organizations.",
